1282–1346","1300–Female":"1300–Deceased","1415":"1415","1337":"1337","1346":"1346","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","about 1330":"about 1330","about 1350?":"about 1350","1282":"1282","Tugford, Shropshire, England":"Tugford, Shropshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pembridge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Pembridge (Herefs), which is recorded as  <i>Penebrug(g)e</i> from the 11th to 14th centuries. The place-name derives from an Old English personal name * <i>Pena</i> + Old English  <i>brycg</i> ‘bridge’. In some cases the surname may be from Pen Bridge in Shipley (Sussex), which derives from an uncertain first element + Old English  <i>brycg</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Pember","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of <b>Pamber</b>, a habitational name from a place in Hampshire named Pamber, from Old English <i>penn</i> ‘fold, enclosure’ + <i>beorg</i> ‘hill’."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":7,"year